Part I - Ford GoBike Exploration¶

by Chukwuebuka Ifechukwu¶

Introduction¶

The dataset contains information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area, information such as duration, start and end time as well as start and end station are recorded. These various attributes will be explored in this report to find insights into the data and find any correlations that exist from it using Python and its various data analysis libraries.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Before embarking on the exploration, the dataset will be explored quickly to wrangle it and ensure it is in the right format for analysis.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  1. Which station was used the most to start?
  2. Which station was did most people end up?
  3. Is there a particular month or period(seasons) in which people biked a whole lot?
  4. Is there a relationship between duration and gender?
  5. Is there a relationship between duration and month/season?
  6. As the day when by did the number of biker and duration increase?

Univariate Exploration¶

Univariate functions¶

Fuctions for plotting different univariate charts

In [ ]:
def bar_chart(data,x,order,hor=False):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
    chart_col = sb.color_palette()[0]
    if hor == False:
        sb.countplot(data=data,x=x,order=order,color=chart_col)
    else:
        sb.countplot(data=data,y=x,order=order,color=chart_col)

def plt_bar_chart(data,x,y):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
    plt.bar(data=data,x=x,height=y)

plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.show()

Question 3¶

Exploring the user type in the dataset and the ratio

In [ ]:
#plotting a bar chart for visualization
x = fordbike_uni['user_type'].value_counts()
order=fordbike_uni['user_type'].value_counts().index
bar_chart(fordbike_uni,'user_type',order=order)
plt.title('User type count')
plt.xlabel('User type')
plt.ylabel('Count')
locs, labels = plt.xticks()  
num = fordbike_uni['user_type'].value_counts().sum()

# loop through each pair of locations and labels 
for loc, label in zip(locs, labels): 
    # get the text property for the label to get the correct count 
    count = x[label.get_text()] 
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/num) 
    # print the annotation just below the top of the bar 
    plt.text(loc, count, pct_string, ha = 'center', color = 'black')
plt.show()

From the visualization, we can see that in the given dataset, approx 91% are subscribers while the remaining are customers

From this histogram, we can see that it is skewed to the right a lot and majority of the individuals journeyed for a duration between 161 and 561 seconds which approximates to between 2.5 and 10 hours

In [ ]:

In [ ]:

labels = ['{}'.format(val) for val in ticks]

plt.title('Duration Seconds Histogram')
plt.xscale('log')

plt.show()

Observations for Univariate Exploration¶

  1. The station most used to start the journey is Market St at 10th St
  2. The station most used to end the journey is San Francisco Caltrain Station 2 (Townsend St at 4th St)
  3. There is a significantly larger amount of subscribers to customers
  4. In the dataset, majority of the individuals are Male followed by Female then others
  5. Majority of people did not want to share their bike for the trip
  6. Majority of people started the journey on Thursday and also ended their journey on Thursday
  7. The distribution of the duration indicates a unimodal distribution and majority can be found below 3500 seconds
  8. The age distribution also inidicates a unimodal distribution and is skewed to the right with the majority found between ages 28 and 33

# Functions for bivariate 

def biv_plot(type,data,x,y):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
    if type =='violin':
        sb.violinplot(data=data,x=x,y=y,inner=None)
    elif type == 'box':
        sb.boxplot(data=data,x=x,y=y)
    elif type =='bar':
        sb.countplot(data=data,x=x,hue=y)

Weekday and Duration¶

For this, the end_weekday was explored as that is the day that the individual would have finished their trip and accumulated all the duration seconds. With this we can see which day had most duration rather than number of individuals that finished that day as seen in the univariate exploration

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
# creating an order for the days of the week
days=['Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday','Saturday','Sunday']

#plotting using barplot from the seaborn library
chart_col = sb.color_palette()[0]
sb.barplot(data=fordbike_biv,x='end_weekday',y='duration_sec',order=days,color=chart_col)
plt.title('Average duration per weekday')
plt.xlabel('Weekday')
plt.ylabel('Average Duration')
plt.xticks(rotation=30)
plt.show()

From this we can see that the most time spent on a trip was actually on the weekend most especially on Sunday. This would resonate with the fact that more people will have more free time then to actually go for a bike ride and spend longer.

#Functions for multivariate

def mul_plot(data,x,y,h):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
    sb.lmplot(data=data,y=y,x=x,hue=h,fit_reg=False)

From all the explorations done, the following were noticed in general

  1. The younger the age, the high chance of biking for a longer period of time especially between 28 and 33
  2. A customer user is more likely to go a longer duration than a subscriber user
  3. Most people began and ended their journey on Thursday whereas the days with the most duration can be found on weekend in particular to Sunday. This of course is relative to the fact that most people have free time on Sunday.
  4. Looking at the days over the month there is no steady increase in the number of people that go for a bike ride, rather it varies up and down
